1053156695583657984.text:
9/ Either way:

1) Paying for more then you intend to use is discouraged 
2) Squatting on domains that you don't really care about is less likely
3) The cost is pretty fair overall. Both for starting and maintaining an existing domain 
4) A shorter time scale encourages recycling

1053156694287626240.text: 8/ If you are further along and more time conscious then price conscious, you could pay 6 months to a year at a time to maintain ownership. $120.00 every 6 months is not that much for an established business or project.

1053156692978995200.text: 7/ This series has the nice property that for any month you can continue paying for the domain name at the same base price. So if you are price conscious one could every month pay the $5.00 (n2 in the series) required to maintain ownership.

1053156691645267968.text:
6/ Example: If the starting value is $5. To pay in advanced it would cost :
1 Months = $ 5.00.
2 Months = $ 10.00 (5+5)
3 Months = $ 20.00 (5 + 5 + 10)
6 Months = $ 120.00 (5 + 5 + 10 + 15 + 35 + 50)

1053156690294697984.text: 5/ One way to do this is with Fibonacci scaled "renting" of the domain name. To buy a domain for 1 month in advanced it would cost n1 in the fibonacci sequence. To buy for 3 months it would cost n3 in the sequence. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number …

1053156688835104768.text: 4/ This means monthly or yearly held Vickrey auctions are unlikely to help keep prices fair to the owner. What is left is to discourage people holding names when they don't need to maintain them.

1053156687505510401.text: 3/ Further problem, is an asymmetry in the consequences for the owner of a domain. The value of disrupting your service (e.g. buying your domain name from under you) to a bad actor can be more valuable to them then it is to you to maintain it.

1053156686238756864.text: 2/ Best mechanism for pricing is the Vickrey auction. This doesn't work well for domains because "when a domain is valuable" is difficult to determine. Speculation is the enemy of fair prices. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vickrey_auction …
